The Higgs Boson analyzes
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs Boson has excited some remarks in the last summer, and this for good reason.
Indeed, it is believed that this Boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism that is responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence of the standard model - our best or "at least false" explanation of nature and behavior of matter - was foretold, but was not yet noticed empirically.
But for the physicists, it is not completely sure that it is really the Higgs.
We know without doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it resembles the Higgs Boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a large physics conference in Kyoto, but there is no data left to be completely safe about it.
Yet, let's assume that it's actually the Higgs, as it seems that there's only a small risk of being deceived, and let's look at what's going on.
There is necessarily an indispensable law in this world that causes that two objects cannot be present simultaneously at the same place.
It is not possible to violate this rule - and do not try it too strong because you will hurt yourself.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that such a law also applies to them: the Pauli's exclusion principle, which says that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time when they are in the same "quent state", with this "condition" largely consists of some of their properties.
From this, physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In a corner are the good citizens who are called Fermione and likely obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the Bosons, an evil band of anarchists who are nothing sacred - in any case not this principle, which means that they can actually be in the same place at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley laboratories (which is, by the way, absolutely amazing) these bosons are divided into two groups: the Mesons that we will not treat here and the "power particles", through which the great forces of nature spread and with whom the Higgs Boson would be related somehow.
But it must be stressed here that these bosons are not all such exotic creatures as you might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "light particle", which is the "both" of the electromagnetic force.
When a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes the direction, the electromagnetic field is "gesturped" exactly in this place, in such a way as a tombstone that was thrown into a pond.
This "destruction" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon and thus one of the bosons "drawers of power".
Stabler Field
The same applies to the Higgs Boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "gesturped" so that this Boson will appear.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must achieve very high energies, a little similar to a frozen pond, whose surface could only be frightened by a very large rock.
Therefore, a huge particle accelerator such as the CERN is required - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a size of 27 km! - to achieve such energy.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, it is not all particles and all materials that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others do not - for example, a paper would never keep itself at the refrigerator.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do it have a mass, while the others (as by other means the photon) have no mass.
For what can all these research now be "good," asks Mrs Plamondon?
For science, they are used to verify the standard model (SM), and they also enable physicists to examine all deviations between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
There are also numerous physicists who hope that such variations will be found, as the least difference could open a door to a "new physics" and stop some holes of the model.
One must say that the latter still has great deficiencies because it does not provide explanations for the gravity (ups!) and the dark matter that forms around 80% of the matter of the universe (new ups!).
However, such deviations have not been found in the CERN until now.
Effects
The impact of these research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there was no.
By the way, in the early 60s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell labs did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but otherwise nothing.
In fact, the deceased physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs in which the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who in 1962 himself developed the first long-term stroke laser (the first were pulsed) - said that at the beginning the laser was considered rather a "lab play".
