It describes Bitcoin as "the virtual currency with the greatest success", "in competition with the dollar or euro" and "like the traditional currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies such as the "crites", which are used to move forward in a video game that can be won or purchased by playing (and sometimes also exchange back).
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, trade is monitored and processed by a central authority each time.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously keepers of the accounting book, auditors, money issuers as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses in the form of an e-mail.
With the difference that the user can choose another address for each payment, which ensures anonymousity.
A number of data related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Using the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the handled bitcoins are available in the public accounts book that is spread throughout the network.
The decisive step is to enter this new transaction into this book.
This is done through a mathematical task launched on the computers, adding this additional line to the winner, who is a type of provisional central banker.
It is a fragment of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and unambiguous electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole is "hacked".
The goal is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (so many zeros at the beginning).
If this number has been found, the other nodes can easily check if it is the right number.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wants to pay with the same money twice very fast (less than 10 minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated from the network and the other would remain without link, as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that has solved the task gets 50 Bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, this reward is regularly halved, probably before the end of 2012.
The bitcoins in circulation are therefore limited to 21 million, but can be shared up to a hundred million pieces, which leaves a certain space...
Furthermore, the difficulty of the task is increased by any improvement in the computation performance.
The life of the network has already had heights and depths.
The websites that provide Bitcoin services were attacked and stolen the Bitcoin deposits.
"The weakness used does not concern the actual protocol," says Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced Paymium, which is a company for paying with real money and using the network Bitcoin.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering using this anonymous service.
