Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the accounting book and showed that almost 80% of Bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November, a "Mega lock sales" was launched.
"Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged," Jon Holmquist, who works for the Coinabul company, is pleased to convert the bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also author of a book about this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
Its system Paytunia corresponds to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses Bitcoin to validate transactions that are cheaper.
In addition, the holder manages its identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented with dealers, and the latter do not have to install new terminals or computer programs.
You just need to specify one address that can be "photographed and recognized" by a phone, specify Pierre Noizat, who assures that he has thousands of users.
It is a general trend in which hierarchical systems are covered in favour of more horizontally oriented systems.
"It'll take some time to pass Bitcoin, but 2013 could be a turning point," he predicts.
