Of course, the path of Poland into space began much earlier.
Before World War II, Polish cosmos enthusiasms were involved in space, not always looking for understanding.
I remember, for example, the lecture of A. Šternfeld of December 6, 1933 in the Warsaw Observatory, in which the author presented thoughts from his pioneer work "Incoming to Cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold, and after years Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
Šternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch founded by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch in 1934.
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important defender of astronomy and space.
In Polish magazines, he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski's worldwide recognised contribution to the development of space was recognized, among other things, by one of the craters being named after him on the moon's edge.
Already in 1925, a railway draisine was built in Poland for which a missile drive was planned.
The author of the draft and the details of this project were unfortunately unknown.
