The information for this is exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933 the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-powered guns.
The research works led the Institut Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
From the documents delivered, it is evident that research has been carried out to the stage of practical tests.
The research was, of course, interrupted by the entry of the German military force.
In 1937, the design of a photo-electric hunting tract appeared in the press of Ing. Rohoziński, and in the following year, the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" was published by the author of Leliwa-Krzywoblocky.
Both projects dealt with the military use of the missile drive.
Shortly before the war, all projects for military use of rocket technology were coordinated by the preceding Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Committee Doradczo-Naukowy).
The Committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of activity, its work was completed from the beginning of the war.
Following the war, further articles on space appeared in the Polish press thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first mention of this society is made in 1954 in the November issue of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles of space are dedicated.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal to establish a space company.
At the time there were already the first satellite technology projects, and it was noted that the research of space would have the future.
Already in their beginnings in 1956, the Polish Space Company PTA sought to join the in 1951 founded International Föderation for Space, and the PTA became a regular member in the autumn of 1956.
The following year the first PTA Chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), deputy president of the International Föderation for Space.
He had this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has contributed significantly to the development of the highly successful meteorological missile (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish missile for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and did not weigh 5 kg.
Later, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built and in 1959 started in the Błędów Desert flight tests with the two-level RM-2 missile.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another level of development should already be able to perform real scientific work - the rocket RM-34 should reach a flight height of up to 14.5 km and be used to observe high winds.
In 1962, however, further development was suspended.
Following the first rockets of type RM, the Meteor-1 missile developed in 1962 to 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage missile, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types of rockets were developed (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed from one another in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A missile had a transport space with 0.4 litres of capacity, meteor-1B over 0.34 litres and meteor-1C over 0.62 litres.
The maximum flight height was 37 km for all three types.
In 1965 to 1968, the Meteor 2 missile was developed in the Aerospace Institute, whose first flight tests started in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to transport a load of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
Afterwards the versions Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning the accession of Poland to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, following the establishment of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites as part of the Intercosmos programme, and in 1978, the Polish Pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became second intercos monaut after the Czech Vladimír Remek.
